uring the medieval period. The articles collected here provoke a fresh look at the relevant sources. The main areas touched by this new research can be divided into five broad categories: deconstructing scholarship on Buddhist/Muslim interactions, cultural and religious exchanges, perceptions of the other, transmission of knowledge, and trade and economics. The subjects covered are wide ranging and demonstrate the vast challenges involved in dealing with historical, social, cultural and economic frameworks that span Central and South Asia of the premodern world. We hope that the results show promise for future research produced on Buddhist and Muslim encounters. The intended audience is specialists in Asian Studies, Buddhist Studies and Islamic Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aBuddhismxRelationsxIslam. 0aBuddhismzAsia, CentralxHistory. 0aBuddhismzSouth AsiaxHistory. 0aIslamxRelationsxBuddhism. 0aIslamzAsia, CentralxHistory. 0aIslamzSouth AsiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aMusk Routes.  aPremodern Buddhism.  aSpread of Islam.  aSufi Islam.1 aAmar, Abhishek S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuer, Blain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuer, Blain, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCappelletti, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDessein, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInaba, Minoru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmiedchen, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSears, Tamara I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlaje, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.